Document: GPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: This section introduces GPU bottlenecks in game development, explaining their potential causes and the challenges in measuring and addressing them.
The demand for new graphics features and progress almost guarantees that you will encounter graphics bottlenecks. Some of these can be on the CPU side, for instance in calculations inside the Godot engine to prepare objects for rendering. Bottlenecks can also occur on the CPU in the graphics driver, which sorts instructions to pass to the GPU, and in the transfer of these instructions. And finally, bottlenecks also occur on the GPU itself. Where bottlenecks occur in rendering is highly hardware-specific. Mobile GPUs in particular may struggle with scenes that run easily on desktop. Understanding and investigating GPU bottlenecks is slightly different to the situation on the CPU. This is because, often, you can only change performance indirectly by changing the instructions you give to the GPU. Also, it may be more difficult to take measurements. In many cases, the only way of measuring performance is by examining changes in the time spent rendering each frame.
---CHUNK---
Document: GPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: This section explains how draw calls, state changes, and graphics APIs impact GPU performance, emphasizing the need to minimize instructions and group similar objects for rendering.
Note: The following section is not relevant to end-users, but is useful to provide background information that is relevant in later sections.
Godot sends instructions to the GPU via a graphics API (Vulkan, OpenGL, OpenGL ES or WebGL). The communication and driver activity involved can be quite costly, especially in OpenGL, OpenGL ES and WebGL. If we can provide these instructions in a way that is preferred by the driver and GPU, we can greatly increase performance.
Nearly every API command in OpenGL requires a certain amount of validation to make sure the GPU is in the correct state. Even seemingly simple commands can lead to a flurry of behind-the-scenes housekeeping. Therefore, the goal is to reduce these instructions to a bare minimum and group together similar objects as much as possible so they can be rendered together, or with the minimum number of these expensive state changes.
---CHUNK---
Document: GPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: Explains the concept of 2D batching for rendering multiple similar items with a single draw call to reduce performance costs.

2D batching
In 2D, the costs of treating each item individually can be prohibitively high - there can easily be thousands of them on the screen. This is why 2D batching is used. Multiple similar items are grouped together and rendered in a batch, via a single draw call, rather than making a separate draw call for each item. In addition, this means state changes, material and texture changes can be kept to a minimum.
---CHUNK---
Document: 3D batching
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: Overview of 3D batching strategies, the trade-offs between draw calls and culling, and the recommendation to join static meshes.

In 3D, the goal is to minimize draw calls and state changes. However, batching several objects into a single draw call is more difficult in 3D than in 2D. 3D meshes often consist of hundreds or thousands of triangles, and combining large meshes in real-time is prohibitively expensive. The cost of joining them quickly exceeds any performance benefits as the number of triangles per mesh grows.

A much better alternative is to join meshes ahead of time for objects that are static in relation to each other. This can be performed by artists during the modeling process or programmatically within Godot using an add-on.

There is a significant cost to batching objects in 3D. Several objects rendered as one cannot be individually culled. For example, an entire city that is off-screen will still be rendered if it is joined to a single blade of grass that is on-screen. Key Rule: Always take objects' locations and culling into account when attempting to batch 3D objects together. Despite this, the benefits of joining static objects often outweigh other considerations, especially for large numbers of distant or low-poly objects.

For more information on 3D specific optimizations, see Optimizing 3D performance.
---CHUNK---
Document: GPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: This section explains how reusing shaders and materials can significantly improve GPU rendering performance in Godot.

Key Rule: Reusing Materials: The fewer different materials in the scene, the faster the rendering will be. If a scene has a huge amount of objects (in the hundreds or thousands), try reusing the materials. In the worst case, use atlases to decrease the amount of texture changes.
Key Rule: Reusing Shaders: If materials can't be reused, at least try to reuse shaders. Note: shaders are automatically reused between StandardMaterial3Ds that share the same configuration (features that are enabled or disabled with a check box) even if they have different parameters.

If a scene has, for example, 20,000 objects with 20,000 different materials each, rendering will be slow. If the same scene has 20,000 objects, but only uses 100 materials, rendering will be much faster.
---CHUNK---
Document: GPU Optimization
Path: godot/tutorials/performance/gpu_optimization.rst
Summary: Explains the difference between pixel cost and vertex cost in GPU rendering, particularly highlighting the performance implications on mobile devices.

Vertex cost versus pixel cost is a crucial concept in GPU optimization. While it's often assumed that fewer polygons mean faster rendering, this is relative and depends on the target hardware.

On modern PCs and consoles, vertex processing is generally inexpensive. Historically, CPUs handled vertex transformations and clipping, and vertices were transferred from main RAM to GPU memory. However, modern GPUs now handle these tasks internally, significantly boosting performance. 3D artists may have a skewed perception of polygon count's impact due to modeling software requiring geometry to reside in CPU memory for editing, which is not representative of game engine performance. Game engines leverage the GPU's efficiency in rendering many triangles.

Mobile devices present a different scenario. Their GPUs are designed for power efficiency due to limited battery life, unlike the power-hungry GPUs of PCs and consoles. Mobile GPUs prioritize avoiding *overdraw*, which is when the same screen pixel is rendered multiple times. For instance, rendering a house and then another house in front of it results in redundant pixel rendering. While PC GPUs can compensate for this with more pixel processors, increasing power consumption, mobile devices cannot.

To achieve efficiency, mobile GPUs employ *tile-based rendering*. This technique divides the screen into a grid, and each cell processes triangles drawn to it, sorting them by depth to minimize overdraw. This improves performance and reduces power usage but can strain vertex performance. Consequently, fewer vertices and triangles can be processed.

Tile-based rendering also struggles with small objects containing a high density of geometry within a small screen area. This concentrates the workload on a single screen tile, significantly slowing down performance as other cells must wait for it to complete.

Key Rule: On mobile, avoid concentrating vertices in small screen areas. If an object appears tiny due to distance, use a lower level of detail (LOD) model. Even on desktop GPUs, it's advisable to avoid rendering triangles smaller than a single pixel on screen.

Additional vertex processing is required for:
- Skinning (skeletal animation)
- Morphs (shape keys)
- Vertex-lit objects (common on mobile)
---CHUNK---
